5 4. praedibusque ac praedfls cavendum populo. This is a customary formula in all cases of security given to the state, and commonly limited to such cases by the words publice, in publicum, or populo. The praecles, written praevides in the lea: ayraria, were the sureties who were bound over; they were to be landowners, and their proedia (praehendia) might be seized upon in case of default (ea pignore data publice mancipio fidem prestant. Varro l. l. v, 40). The lega] charac- teristics of these proedia are stated Cic. pro Flacc. 32. 79, quaero simne ista pradia censui censendo, habeant ius civile, sint necne sint mancipii, that is, they must be freehold under strict Roman law. The formula. occurs in the Lex Malacitana of the lst century of the Empire, where see the comment of Mommsen, p. 470.
